Children 3 - 12 years old. My goal has been to make this book interesting and understandable not only for children of all ages, but also for their parents. Thus, the book is divided into several parts: the story itself, which includes history and fable; folkloric narrative on how people really live; and an educational section at the end of the story for parents to discuss with their children. A long time ago, in a place where great roads crossed, stood the City of Blue Domes, with its narrow, winding streets and intricate mosaics decorating its high towers. The ruler of that city was the powerful Emir Bahriddin, the wisest of the wise and first among the just.One spring morning, Emir Bahriddin was reclining among his pillows in his Room of Thought. Ancient books in leather covers lined the shelves, maps of stars and land caravan routes hung on the walls. The room's large carved windows looked out onto a green, ever-blooming garden with cooling fountains.he emir liked to come to this room to ponder on life’s problems or think through an affair of State.  Here, with the song of birds drifting in from the garden, he could concentrate, search for answers in his books, and consult with learned elders.This time, Emir Bahriddin had a most difficult task to solve. Spring had finally come – the time for sowing in the fields – but after two years with poor harvests, the people had no seed to sow.  The ruler did not yet know how he would feed his subjects this year. It was in the midst of these sad thoughts that his wife found him. I have been working on this project for two years. In 2019, I travelled to the region for the research in the field, essential to the final product. I spoke to art experts, and craftspeople; visited crafts workshops and museums; took pictures, recorded video, and made sketches. All of this research was used directly in the story and illustrations, and in the Ethnographic Notes and activity sections of the book.In 2019, my book project “Introducing Central Asia through Children’s Literature” received Honorable Mention in the Public Outreach Award from Central Eurasian Studies Society.Marina Abrams – Author of book series, The World of Barzu; project director and founder of “Barzu World.” I was born and raised in Kazakhstan, lived in Tajikistan and Russia, and traveled extensively around the Eurasian region. I am an international policy professional with twenty years of experience in multi-disciplinary projects. I hold a B.A. in Translation-Interpretation from the Abylaikhan Kazakh State University of International Relations and World Languages and an M.A. in International Policy Studies from the Middlebury Institute of International Studies at Monterey, where I studied on a Graduate Muskie Merit Scholarship. I have two children. More information on my website:  https://marinaabrams.com/ Gulya Gromova- Djumagari –  illustrator, was born and raised in Uzbekistan, where she graduated from Republican Art College of P.P. Benkov and then studied at the Tashkent Theatre and Art Institute. She is a member of the International Federation of Artists (IFA) and the Union of Artists of Uzbekistan. Since 2007, Gulya lives and works in Almaty, Kazakhstan. More information on her website:  http://gromova.info/biography.html Joshua Abrams – translator from Russian into English. My husband, a wonderful father to my children, and a talented writer. Joshua studied Russian in St Petersburg, was a Peace Corps Volunteer in Kazakhstan, and has lived and worked in most of the countries of the former Soviet Union. He’s a graduate of Bard College (BA) and Indiana University (MPA/MA) and has also published his own articles and stories. Natalia Kuzmina – editor of the original text in Russian. Natalia is a graduate of the Philology Department at Novosibirsk State University, Russia. From 1993 to 1996 Natalia and I studied together in the Philology Group at Specialized High School #134 in Almaty, Kazakhstan. And now, 20 years later we are happy to work together in this project. Most important, Natalia is a mother of four wonderful boys.

Each month, Mexico’s extensive rail network unwillingly serves thousands of undocumented people from across Latin America and beyond. Apart from walking, this dangerous method of transportation is the only free ticket north for the passengers who are attempting to reach the United States. As La Bestia slowly traverses Mexico’s rugged landscape, these passengers are exposed to the subterranean environment of Mexico’s criminal and cartel underworld, often referred to as the ‘Cachuco’ industry - an illicit market that aims to profit from migrants in any way possible…
 
Juan's story:
"Juan first travelled alone from rural Guatemala to the United States in 1999 at the age of 14. To date, he has made the journey between the two countries six times. On his numerous rides atop La Bestia, he has witnessed other migrants lose limbs or fall to their death. He has been kidnapped, extorted and robbed by local gangs, drug cartels and even the police. A little over a year ago, he was pulled over on his way home from work at a fast food restaurant in Oklahoma, where his wife, sister and two children also live. The police officer asked Juan, “do you know why I pulled you over? Because you’re brown. I don’t like brown people”. Not being able to produce any documentation, he was deported after being held for months in an ICE detention facility. He will likely never be able to reunite with his family north of the border; but after twenty years in the US, he has nothing to return to in Guatemala either."
 The book:‘Sueño Americano’ is a short book (in A5) which explores personal stories and the greater political and historical implications of the Latin American migrant trail in Mexico to the US. More specifically, the book examines migration which utilises Mexico's extensive and dangerous freight train network, referred to simply as ‘La Bestia’ (The Beast), where up to 20,000 migrants are kidnapped each year, traversing some of the most violent regions in the world. Find the detailed description of the contents below.Almost all of the groundwork for the book is complete and with your backing, we can afford the upfront costs to print, distribute and advertise Sueño Americano on this pre-order basis, as well as pay the contributors for their work prior to shipping.The film:Also, as featured at the top of this fundraiser, a short film is being produced in conjunction with the booklet which will not be available publicly, but will be made available for backers of the book, and serves now as a video trailer for the Sueño Americano project as a whole. The final film will be between 15-20 minutes in length.Our mission:30% of all net proceeds will be donated to 14 individual charities and critical groups working to protect children separated from their families by ICE (U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement). Between October 2018 and September 2019, the journeys of 72,873 unaccompanied children ended with apprehension at the U.S. southwest border (UNICEF USA). For more information on the individual charities, click here.  A further 10% of the net proceeds will be donated to ‘Medicines Sans Frontières’ (Doctors Without Borders) for their humanitarian work with migrants and vulnerable people worldwide during this global pandemic, which has stretched medical resources further than any other period in recent history. Why would you be interested in Sueño Americano?To answer this question, we would like to borrow the words of the Salvadoran journalist and writer Óscar Martínez:“My proposal is that you know what is going on. What [people who are migrating to the US] are living through. Because I believe that knowing is different from not knowing. I believe that knowing … is the beginning of the solution. I believe, sticking with the metaphor of the sea [that erodes] the rock, that knowing is what moves the waves. You can be one of the waves.”I have invested many thousands of pounds into this project, excluding costs of equipment and labour time. We are not concerned with recouping this investment through the book, we merely wish to meet our expenses and generate funds for the aforementioned organisations, while raising awareness of migration in Mexico in a holistic context. There is a notable lack of media coverage for Latin American migration in the UK and Europe, which was one of the original motivations for this project. History of the project: Between the physical dangers of La Bestia, Mexico’s widespread criminal activity, and global quarantines, it has been a significant challenge to bring this project to life, which is the culmination of two years of first-hand research and four trips to the United States and Mexico. I am extremely grateful for the hospitality I recieved from strangers and friends alike in Mexico, Along with the input of my many collaborators, without whom, this project would not be possible. In the process of compiling a guide with rail information to help people travel on La Bestia, one of my collaborators was unfortunately kidnapped by the cartel in Nuevo Laredo, Mexico. He survived and was returned to the US after this event, but this illustrates the risks anyone takes to get a glimpse of the world of Mexico’s most vulnerable. Despite global lockdowns, I was able to continue the research for this book, utilising the connections I had already made in Mexico and Central America. I am now conducting phone interviews from the UK to be able to finish the research for this project to the fullest extent. Contents:Part 1 - History and Context:Initially, Sueño Americano will contain a historical and socio-political exploration of the migration of many Latin Americans through Mexico to the USA. This historical analysis will begin in the late 1800s, examining the United States involvement within Mexican economics and the Mexican revolution of 1910, as well as the creation of the Mexican rail network and its utilisation by US corporations operating in Latin America. Continuing, the book will examine a series of complex US foreign policy-based decisions utilising disclosed government branch documents. This will begin with an analysis of the ‘Monroe Doctrine’ and its use in the ending of European colonial rule in Mexico, and how this doctrine was later repurposed to give the US more control over the economies and resources of Latin America. The book then explores the “Red Scare” era of American foreign policy after the Cuban revolution, and its attempts to quell the growth of socialism and communism in Latin America by any means necessary. This was to attempt to sustain the United States field of influence in the region over other political forces under the administrations of presidents ranging from Eisenhower to Clinton, as well as the involvements of Henry Kissinger and the lobbying of private companies.In-depth case studies will be conducted showing CIA-led interventions in states with democratically elected socialist politicians to curb the spread of the ideology, by funding and often training many paramilitary right-wing groups which conducted mass killings and attempted forms of ethnic cleansing. This, in effect, will showcase how the destabilisation and suppression bred the perfect environment for illicit trade, the rise of the cartels, and the formation of the powerful gangs in the US which now control Central America and beyond, sustaining the mass Latin-American migration to the US of the past 60 years. Part 2 - Today’s Politics and Fieldwork:The second part of Sueño Americano will explore today's physical and political situation in Mexico, Central America and the US regarding migration. The book will examine recent policy making and political attitudes relating to migrants in Mexico and the US, as well as utilising extensive research and statistical data to highlight the situations and dangers for migrants while travelling across Mexico. The psychological implications of this journey will then be examined using case studies and original interviews by our collaborator in Chihuahua Mexico. Detailed accounts will be told of the journey and risks of La Bestia, interactions with police and criminal organisations, kidnappings, detentions by US police and help from Mexican organisations and individuals. Not only this, but personal accounts will be shared exploring the reasons that prompted migrants to leave their countries of origin in search of asylum. Part 3 - Personal Experiences:As well as what is already mentioned, the final part of the book will give some brief insight into my personal journey and motivations for undertaking this fieldwork, from the first time I rode a freight train at the age of 17, until my latest trip to Mexico. We will explore some more detailed illustrated stories of my 100’s of hours of travel on La Bestia, as well as friends' and collaborators' stories of their own experiences travelling and riding freight trains in Mexico. Final Points:All text and research will be fully referenced, and resources for additional reading/viewing will also be included at the end, as well as a list of the charities we will donate to and a brief description of their work. Ultimately, Sueño Americano aims to serve both the casual reader with an interest in global migration and/or US/Mexico politics, and also provide a more holistic picture of why migration to the US exists in the way it does today for a more informed reader of the subject. Illustrations, Objects and Photos:All of this will be supported by a powerful collection of illustrations and photos from various authors, as well as stills from the film to represent the people interviewed in the fieldwork, as well as other situations that are discussed in the text. There will also be a series of photographs of physical objects collected by myself or others during the fieldwork as pictured below.Some Context Regarding Migration in Mexico (click for more info)Timeline:Below is the estimated timeline for the project development and production. We aim to print the first batch in November 2020, however, the timing is subject to changes in case of new lockdown/social distancing measures that might affect the production times. Contributors:Content creation:Mouse Green is an artist based in London, UK, who works with analogue and digital video, as well as photography and installation. He has previously shown work at the Shanghai Biennale and British Library. He graduated with a first-class honours degree in Fine Art from Central Saint Martins. Current project 'Sueño Americano' was partially sponsored by the Mead Fellowship.Ario Daniso is a researcher based in London, originating from Iran and Italy. He is a native speaker of Farsi and Italian, with English as an acquired mother tongue, and fluency in French and Spanish. He specialises in the analysis of left-wing movements and human rights issues. He has worked with NGOs such as Migrants Organise. Ario holds an undergraduate and Masters in International Relations, as well as a postgraduate degree in international human resource management and has published works including ‘Rojava, An Anarchist Utopia?’.Ayur Sandoval is a researcher based in Chihuahua, Mexico, who graduated in psychology and is a currently working towards completing a master's degree in legal psychology from the Sigmund Freud faculty of psychology in Chihuahua City, Mexico. He has previously worked as a librarian at the aforementioned university, and as a facilitator at the Civil Association Centre for Family Intelligence, which serves troubled teens.  Owen Ekert is a YouTuber and blogger who runs the channel entitled 'Ranoutonarail'. Over the past two years, he has documented his experience of riding more than 50 freight trains across Mexico.Trailer voiceover performed by Yaatzil Ceballos Fernandez. Special thanks to: 

